The '''Grammy Awards''' (first named the '''Gramophone Awards''' and often called just '''Grammys'''), are awards given yearly by the [[:en:National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|Recording Academy]] (an association of Americans professionally involved in the recorded music industry) for outstanding work in the [[music]] and spoken recording industry. The Grammys have 108 categories with 30 genres. The Grammys are awarded once each year and are a major televised event.

The name "Grammy" comes from the word "gramophone". A gramophone was an old machine that played [[music]] on [[vinyl record|records]].<ref>http://rs6.loc.gov/ammem/berlhtml/berlgramo.html</ref>

The British equivalent is the [[BRIT Awards|Brit Awards]]. The Canadian equivalent is the Juno Awards.

[[Georg Solti]] has won 31 Grammy Awards, more than any other person.<ref>http://www.nytimes.com/2003/02/23/arts/music-the-grammys-classical-fewer-records-more-attention.html</ref>

